<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25106e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25106e">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25106e"> 106(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> round table / &mdash; tower</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> Wace&apos;s literary celebrity is due, perhaps, most of all to the fact that he is the first Arthurian writer to mention the <mark>Round Table</mark>. &ldquo;The Bretons,&rdquo; he says, &ldquo;tell many a fable of the Table Round,&rdquo; but he does not explain whence such fables came, or where he heard them told. He does, however, inform us that the Table was made round because each of Arthur&apos;s knights thought himself better than his fellows, and Arthur devised this method of settling all disputes about precedence among them. <small> W. Lewis Jones, <a name="WJKA2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WJKA2"><cite title="source">King Arthur in History and Legend</cite></a> (1914) 90f</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also <a name="n53093o" href="n53all.htm#n53093o">N53 (VI.B.46):093(o)</a>  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c14065c" href="c14all.htm#c14065c">VI.C.14:065(c)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
